          <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0001">1</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">For the nature of the documents presented here, see the Editorial Note, above. The negotiations that effectively ended on 14 March 1785, with the commissioners response to the Prussian Observations on the treaty, resulted in changes, some minor and others of more substance, to the preamble and Arts. 2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 9, 10, 12, 13, 21, 25, and 27. This meant that the revised text of the treaty sent by Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson to the Baron von Thulemeier on 26 May was virtually identical to the treaty as concluded on 10 September. In the notes below, the points at which changes were made are indicated and deleted material is identified, but for the text of language inserted at the behest of either party, see the Prussian and American commentaries on the treaty, Nos. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0007" class="document">VI</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0009" class="document">VIII</a>, below.</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0002">2</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">To this point this passage was included virtually verbatim at the beginning of the preamble to the 10 Sept. treaty, while the following sentence, slightly altered, came at the end. There is no mention of the preamble in any of the letters between the commissioners and Thulemeier, but in the final treaty it was much longer, including the names and offices of the Prussian and American
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0398">[398<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0398.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
negotiators derived from their commissions. The revised preamble was presumably added by Franklin and Jefferson when they prepared the final English text of the treaty (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;Treaties and Other International Acts of the United States of America,&lt;/i&gt; ed. Hunter Miller, Washington, D.C., 19311948; 8 vols. ]">Miller, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Treaties,</span></span> 2:162163).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0003-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0003">3</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The text to this point in both this and the following article is retained verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty, but there an additional passage was added requiring reciprocal adherence to established laws &amp; usages (same, p. 163165).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0004-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0004">4</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">To this point the language of this article is retained verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty, but there a long passage was added requiring a reciprocal observance of laws prohibiting the import or export of particular goods or merchandise (same, p. 165166).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0005-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0005">5</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The passage from this point to the words be forced to unload in the English text and ne seront pas forcs in the French text was deleted. The remainder, with minor changes in wording and the proper connectives, was retained (same, p. 166).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0006-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0006">6</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">On the French translation, regarding a Prussian proposed change and the American response, the remainder of the article was placed in brackets and Franklin wrote, Omit these Lines, if the proposd Addition is allowd. In the end an additional passage was added to the 10 Sept. treaty indicating that the exemption from paying duties charges or fees did not extend to charges assessed for the ports upkeep (same, p. 167168), but see also the exchange regarding Art. 8 in Nos. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0007" class="document">VI</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0009" class="document">VIII</a>, below.</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0007-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0007">7</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">This article was retained verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty, but there a sentence was added abolishing the antient &amp; Barbarous right to wrecks of the sea (same, p. 168).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0008-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0008">8</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">This article was retained verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty, but there language was added prohibiting the government of either nation from exercising a right of detraction and exempting from the articles effect any Prussian law preventing emigration (same, p. 168170).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0009-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0009">9</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The remainder of this article was deleted in the 10 Sept. treaty (same, p. 170171).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0010-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0010">10</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">At this point in the French translation, regarding a Prussian proposed change and the American response, a caret was placed to indicate a possible insertion. Franklin wrote, which Compensation, in Case of Dispute, shall be determined by Arbitrators mutually chosen from among the Merch[ants] of a neutral Nation. Query, if some such Addit[ion] as the above may not answer the Objection? For the exchange over Art. 13, see Nos. <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0007" class="document">VI</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0009" class="document">VIII</a>, below.</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0011-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0011">11</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">This article was retained verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty, but there a passage was added providing that if the master of the ship surrendered the contraband when stopped, he would not be taken into port and could proceed on his voyage (same, p. 171172).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0012-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0012">12</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">In the French translation the commissioners apparently added parentheses here to match the English text.</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0013-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0013">13</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Except for the addition at this point of a clause indicating that such judgments were to be made by the respective nations judicial system, this article was included verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty (same, p. 176177).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0014-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0014">14</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">This article was retained verbatim in the 10 Sept. treaty, but a passage was added providing that if a consul engaged in commerce, he would be subject to the same laws as private merchants (same, p. 181182).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0015-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0015">15</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">In the treaty of 10 Sept. it was stipulated that the treaty would last ten years (same, p. 182).</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0016-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0003-fn-0016">16</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">In the treaty of 10 Sept. this article was followed by an oath concerning the validity of the signatures that followed and the signatures of Thulemeier, Jefferson, Franklin, and <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> (same, p. 183).</p>

          </div>

        </div>
      <div class="docback">
</div>
</div>
      <div class="doc">
        
        <h2>III. The American Commissioners Memorandum<br/>in Support of Article 23 of the Draft<br/>Prussian-American Treaty of Amity and Commerce</h2>
        <div class="docbody">
          <div class="opener">
            <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationRight">[<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">10 November 1784</span>]<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0004-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0004-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></td>
		</tr>
      </table>
          </div>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">By the original Law of Nations war and extirpation was the punishment of injuryhumanizing by degrees, it admitted slavery instead of death. A farther step was, the exchange of prisoners instead
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0399">[399<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0399.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
of slavery. Another, to respect more the property of private persons under conquest, and be content with acquired dominion. Why should not this Law of Nations go on improving? Ages have intervened between its several steps; but as knowledge of late encreases rapidly, why should not those steps be quickened? Why should it not be agreed to as the future law of Nations that in any war hereafter the following discriptions of men should be undisturbed, have the protection of both sides, &amp; be permitted to follow their employments in surety, viz.</p>
          <ul class="simple">
	      <li>1. Cultivators of the earth, because they labour for the subsistance of mankind.</li>
	      <li>2. Fishermen, for the same reason.</li>
	      <li>3. Merchants &amp; Traders in unarmed ships; who accomodate different Nations by communicating &amp; exchanging the necessaries &amp; conveniencies of life.</li>
	      <li>4. Artists &amp; Mechanics inhabiting &amp; working in open towns.</li>
	    </ul>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">It is hardly necessary to add that the Hospitals of Enemies should be unmolested, they ought to be assisted.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">It is for the interest of humanity in general, that the occasions of war, &amp; the inducements to it should be diminished.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">If rapine is abolished, one of the encouragements to war is taken away, &amp; peace therefore more likely to continue &amp; be lasting.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The practice of robbing merchants on the high seas, a remnant of the antient piracy, tho it may be accidentally beneficial to particular persons, is far from being profitable to all engaged in it or to the nation that authorizes it. In the beginning of a war some rich ships, not upon their guard, are surprized &amp; taken. This encourages the first adventurers to fit out more armed vessels, and many others to do the samebut the Enemy at the same time, become more careful, arm their merchant ships better &amp; render them not so easy to be taken they go also more under the protection of convoys Thus while the privateers, to take them are multiplied; the vessels subject to be taken &amp; the chances of profit are diminished, so that many cruises are make wherein the expences overgo the gains;as it is the case in other lotteries, tho particulars have got prizes the mass of Adventurers are losers, the whole expence of fitting out all the privateers during a war, being much greater than the whole amount of goods taken. Then there is the national loss of all the labour of so many men during the time they have been employed in robbing; who besides spend what they get in riot, drunkenness, and debauchery, lose their habits of industry, are rarely fit for any sober
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0400">[400<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0400.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
business after a peace, and serve only to encrease the number of Higwaymen &amp; House-breakers. Even the Undertakers who have been fortunate, are by sudden wealth led into expensive living, the habit of which continues when the means of supporting it cease, and finally ruins them. A just punishment for their having wantonly &amp; unfeelingly ruined many honest innocent Traders and their families, whose substance was employed in serving the common interests of Mankind.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="docback">
          <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0004-sn">
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ manuscript ]">MS</abbr> in David Humphreys hand (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early nineteenth century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e., the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 116, f. 103107).</p>

          </div>
          <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0004-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0004-fn-0001">1</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The editors of the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers of Thomas Jefferson</span> attribute the authorship of this memorandum to Jefferson (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Papers of Thomas Jefferson,&lt;/i&gt; ed. Julian P. Boyd, Charles T. Cullen, John Catanzariti, Barbara B. Oberg, and others, Princeton, 1950. ]">Jefferson, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Papers,</span></span> 7:492493). However, the ideas expressed in the document, as well as in Art. 23 of the draft treaty, are those long held by Benjamin Franklin and approved of by <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>. For the history of Franklins proposals to exempt the Cultivators of the earth, fishermen, and others from the rigors of war, and even to ban the issuance of letters of marque, see the fourth of the commissioners <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0105" class="document">7 May</a> instructions, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0105&amp;expandNote=ADMS-06-16-02-0105-fn-0004#ADMS-06-16-02-0105-fn-0004" class="document">note 4</a>, above.</p>

          </div>

        </div>
      <div class="docback">
</div>
</div>
      <div class="doc">
        
        <h2>IV. The Baron von Thulemeier<br/>to the American Commissioners</h2>
        <div class="docbody">
          <div class="opener">
            <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationLeft">Messieurs,</td>
		  <td class="salutationRight"> la Haye, le 10. Dcembre 1784.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></td>
		</tr>
      </table>
          </div>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">La lettre dont Vous mavez honor, Messieurs, en date du 10 de Novembre ne mest parvenue que le 26 du mme mois, par la voye dun courier Hollandois. Jai transmis au Roi une traduction franoise du Projet dun Trait de Commerce  conclure pour lavantage rciproque des Sujets de Sa Majest et des Citoyens des Etats-Unis de lAmrique, auquel les instructions rcentes du Congrs Vous ont obligs de faire subir quelques altrations, en opposition de celui que javois eu lhonneur de mettre entre les mains de Monsieur Adams le 9. dAvril de lanne courante. Ds que les ordres de ma Cour me seront parvenus, je mempresserai, Messieurs, de Vous informer des observations que le Roi aura cru devoir se permettre sur ce nouveau Projet. Larticle 23. est dict par le zle le plus pur en faveur de lhumanit. Rien de plus juste que les rflexions sur le noble dsintressement des Etats-Unis dAmrique. Il est  desirer que ces sentimens sublimes soyent adopts par toutes les Puissances Maritimes sans exception. Les calamits de la guerre seroient alors de beaucoup adoucies, et les hostilits, souvent provoques par la cupidit et lamour dsordonn du gain, moins rptes.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Agrez, Messieurs, que je retrace  Votre Souvenir la requisition que jai eu lhonneur de Vous faire par les dernires lignes de ma
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0401">[401<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0401.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
lettre du 18. Octobre de cette anne.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> Le Roi mayant tmoign quil apprendroit avec plaisir le choix que les Etats-Unis dAmrique pourroient faire de prfrence de telle ou autre ville pour le commerce dchange entre les ngocians des deux Nations, je Vous suppliai de me faire connotre Vos ides  cet gard. Jajoutai que Stettin, Emden, places maritimes Prussiennes, mme quelques ports de France ou dHollande, rempliroient galement ce but.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Jai lhonneur dtre avec la considration la plus distingue, / Messieurs, / Vtre trs humble et trs obissant Serviteur</p>
          <div class="closer">
            <p class="signed">de Thulemeier</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="translation">
          <h3 style="text-indent: 0; font-size: inherit; font-weight: normal; text-align: center; text-indent: 0;">TRANSLATION</h3>
          <div class="opener">
            <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		  <td class="salutationLeft">Gentlemen</td>
		  <td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 10 December 1784<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></td>
		</tr>
      </table>
          </div>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">The letter of 10 November with which you honored me, gentlemen, reached me by means of a Dutch courier only on the 26th. I transmitted to the king a French translation of the draft treaty of commerce to be concluded for the reciprocal advantage of the subjects of His Majesty and the citizens of the United States of America, to which the recent instructions of Congress obliged you to make a few alterations at variance with the one that I had the honor of putting in the hands of Mr. Adams on 9 April of this year. As soon as orders from my court reach me, I will hasten to inform you, gentlemen, of the observations that the king believes he must make on this new draft. Article 23 is dictated by the purest zeal for the good of humanity. Nothing could be fairer than the reflections on the noble disinterestedness of the United States of America. It is to be desired that these sublime sentiments should be adopted by all maritime powers without exception. The calamities of war would then be much relieved, and the hostilities often provoked by cupidity and the immoderate love of gain, less often repeated.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Please receive kindly, gentlemen, my recalling to mind the request that I had the honor to make you in the last lines of my 18 October letter.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> The king having informed me that he would learn with pleasure the choice of the United States indicating a preference for one city or another where the exchange of commerce between merchants of the two nations might take place, I beseeched you to let me know your ideas on this matter. I added that Stettin or Emden, Prussian ports of trade, as well as several French or Dutch ports could equally serve this purpose.</p>
          <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">I have the honor of being with the most distinguished consideration, gentlemen, your very humble and very obedient servant</p>
          <div class="closer">
            <p class="signed">de Thulemeier</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="docback">
          <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-sn">
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;"><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Papers of the Continental Congress. Originals in the National Archives: Record Group 360. Microfilm edition in 204 reels. Usually cited in the present work from the microfilms, but according to the original series and volume numbering devised in the State Department in the early nineteenth century; for example, PCC, No. 93, III, i.e., the third volume of series 93.&lt;/expan&gt; ]">PCC</span>, No. 86, f. 8184); internal address: Messieurs Adams, Franklin et Jefferson: / Ministres Plenipotentiares des Etats-Unis / de lAmrique  la Cour de
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0402">[402<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-16/ADMS-06-16-02-pb-0402.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>
S. M. T. C. /  Paris.; endorsed: Hague Dec<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> 10<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">th.</span> 1784 / from / Baron de Thulemeier. <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ file copy (Ordinarily a copy of a letter retained by a correspondent &lt;i&gt;other than an Adams&lt;/i&gt;; for example, Jeffersons press copies and polygraph copies, since all three of the Adams statesmen systematically entered copies of their outgoing letters in letterbooks.) ]">FC</abbr> (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>).</p>

          </div>
          <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0001">1</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">Thulemeier also wrote a short note to <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr> on this date (<span class="ref-terms" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;expan&gt;Manuscripts and other materials, 16391889, in the Adams Manuscript Trust collection given to the Massachusetts Historical Society in 1956 and enlarged by a few additions of family papers since then. Citations in the present edition are simply by date of the original document if the original is in the main chronological series of the Papers and therefore readily found in the microfilm edition of the Adams Papers (see below).&lt;/expan&gt; ]">Adams Papers</span>) in which he acknowledged <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ John Adams (17351826) ]">JA</abbr>s <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0248" class="document">letter of 19 Nov.</a>, which Thulemeier had received at the same time as the commissioners <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0002" class="document">letter of 10 November.</a> His <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0242-0005" class="document">10 Dec.</a> letter to the commissioners was likely an enclosure to that note.</p>

          </div>

          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-16-02-0242-0005-fn-0002">2</a>
            
   <p style="text-indent: 1.5em; text-align: left;">This is presumably an inadvertence, and Thulemeier means his <a href="default.xqy?keys=ADMS-print-06-16-02-0221" class="document">letter of 8 Oct.</a>, above.</p>

          </div>

        </div>
      <div class="docback">
